BASELINE ANALYSES

Filtering baseline data and factoring categorical variables:

#Separating baseline results 
time1 <- dt |> filter(Timepoint == 1)

#Factoring categorical variables 
time1$Mono.1.Bi.2 <- factor(time1$Mono.1.Bi.2, levels = c(1,2), labels = c("Monolingual", "Bilingual"))
time1$Gender <- factor(time1$Gender, levels = c(1,2), labels = c("Male", "Female"))

Running regression model #1 ~ on ALL data:

#Factoring disease variants and renaming for clarity:
time1$Variant <- factor(time1$Dx, levels = c("bv","lv","nfv","sv"), labels = c("bvFTD", "lvPPA", "nfvPPA", "svPPA"))

#Extracting the outcome variable names for function; making lists to store results
baseline_outcomes <- colnames(time1)[16:41]
baseline_results <- list()

#Renaming variables for clarity: 
time1$Lingual_Status <- time1$Mono.1.Bi.2
time1$Age_At_Data_Collection <- time1$AgeAtDC
time1$Education <- time1$Educ

#Writing for loop to store all results for baseline linear regression 
for (outcome in baseline_outcomes){
  baseline_formula <- formula(paste(outcome, "~", "Lingual_Status + Variant + Lingual_Status*Variant + Gender + Education + Age_At_Data_Collection"))
  baseline_results[[outcome]] <- lm(baseline_formula, data=time1)
  }

LONGITUDINAL ANALYSES

Filtering for patients with both timepoints and cleaning data:

#Filtering out data 
patients_with_both_timepoints <- dt |> 
  group_by(PIDN) |>  
  filter(all(c(1, 2) %in% Timepoint)) |> 
  ungroup()

timepoint_1_2 <- dt |> 
  filter(PIDN %in% patients_with_both_timepoints$PIDN) |>  
  filter(Timepoint %in% c(1, 2))  

#Factoring categorical variables and renaming variables for clarity:
timepoint_1_2$Gender <- factor(timepoint_1_2$Gender, levels=c(1,2), labels=c("Male", "Female"))
timepoint_1_2$Lingual_Status <- factor(timepoint_1_2$Mono.1.Bi.2, levels=c(1,2), labels=c("Monolingual", "Bilingual"))
timepoint_1_2$Timepoint <- factor(timepoint_1_2$Timepoint, levels=c(1,2), labels=c("Time 1", "Time 2"))
timepoint_1_2$Education <- timepoint_1_2$Educ
timepoint_1_2$Age_At_Data_Collection <- timepoint_1_2$AgeAtDC

Calculating time between data collection in years:

timepoint_1_2$DCDate <- as.Date(timepoint_1_2$DCDate, format="%m/%d/%y")
calculating_date <- timepoint_1_2[, c(1,2,14)]
wide_dc_date <- reshape(calculating_date, idvar="PIDN", timevar = "Timepoint", v.names="DCDate", direction="wide")
wide_dc_date$Time_In_Between <- as.numeric(difftime(wide_dc_date$`DCDate.Time 2`, wide_dc_date$`DCDate.Time 1`, units="days") / 365.2422)

timepoint_1_2 <- timepoint_1_2 |> 
  left_join(wide_dc_date |> select(PIDN, Time_In_Between), by = "PIDN") |> 
  mutate(Time_In_Years = ifelse(Timepoint == "Time 1", 0, Time_In_Between))

Running linear mixed effects model #1 ~ on all data:

#Factoring disease variants and renaming for clarity:
timepoint_1_2$Variant <- factor(timepoint_1_2$Dx, levels = c("bv","lv","nfv","sv"), labels = c("bvFTD", "lvPPA", "nfvPPA", "svPPA"))

#Extracting the outcome variable names for function; making lists to store results
longitudinal_outcomes <- colnames(timepoint_1_2)[16:41]
longitudinal_results <- list()


#Writing for loop to store all results for linear mixed effect models  
for (var in longitudinal_outcomes){
longitudinal_formula <- as.formula(paste(var, "~ Lingual_Status + Education + Age_At_Data_Collection + Gender + Variant + Variant*Lingual_Status + Time_In_Years + (1 | PIDN)"))
longitudinal_results[[var]] <- lmer(longitudinal_formula, data=timepoint_1_2)}

Running linear mixed effects model #2 ~ bvFTD vs PPA (svPPA, lvPPA, and nfvPPA) as a categorical variable:

#Creating the variant variable and factoring 
timepoint_1_2$Variant <- ifelse(timepoint_1_2$Dx == "bv", "bvFTD", "PPA_Variant")
timepoint_1_2$Variant <- factor(timepoint_1_2$Variant, levels = c("bvFTD", "PPA_Variant"), labels = c("bvFTD", "PPA_Variant"))
timepoint_1_2$Variant <- relevel(timepoint_1_2$Variant, ref = "PPA_Variant")

#Extracting the outcome variable names for function; making lists to store results
longitudinal_outcomes <- colnames(timepoint_1_2)[16:41]
longitudinal_results_cat <- list()


#Writing for loop to store all results for linear mixed effect models  
for (var in longitudinal_outcomes){
longitudinal_formula_cat <- as.formula(paste(var, "~ Education + Time_In_Years + Age_At_Data_Collection + Gender + Variant*Lingual_Status + (1 | PIDN)"))
longitudinal_results_cat[[var]] <- lmer(longitudinal_formula_cat, data=timepoint_1_2)}

baseline_n <- time1 |> 
  group_by(Lingual_Status, Variant) |> 
  summarise(across(16:41, ~ sum(!is.na(.)), .names = "{.col}_complete"))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Lingual_Status'. You can override using
## the `.groups` argument.
longitudinal_n <- timepoint_1_2 |> 
  group_by(Lingual_Status, Variant) |> 
  summarise(across(16:41, ~ sum(!is.na(.)), .names = "{.col}_complete"))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Lingual_Status'. You can override using
## the `.groups` argument.
mono_vs_bi_baseline <- baseline_n |> group_by(Lingual_Status) |> summarise(across(2:27, sum))
mono_vs_bi_longitudinal <- longitudinal_n |> group_by(Lingual_Status) |> summarise(across(2:27, sum))

Getting averages and SDs for patients in timepoint 1-2 by variant and lingual status

avg_longitudinal <- timepoint_1_2 |> 
  select(PIDN, Variant, Lingual_Status, MMSETot:GDSTot) |>  
  group_by(PIDN) |> 
  summarize(
    Variant = first(Variant),
    Lingual_Status = first(Lingual_Status),
    across(MMSETot:GDSTot, ~ mean(.x, na.rm = TRUE)))

bvftd_longitudinal <- avg_longitudinal |> filter(Variant == "bvFTD")
svppa_longitudinal <- avg_longitudinal |> filter(Variant == "svPPA")
nfvppa_longitudinal <- avg_longitudinal |> filter(Variant == "nfvPPA")
lvppa_longitudinal <- avg_longitudinal |> filter(Variant == "lvPPA")
